<paragraph blockId="28.[151,603,344,406]" box="[151,238,380,406]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,229,380,406]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,739,457,512]" box="[151,739,457,481]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,457,481]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Type-species</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Kupriyanova, 1993 b" authorityName="Kupriyanova" authorityYear="1993" box="[308,739,457,480]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyditrupa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hovei">
<emphasis box="[308,513,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bathyditrupa hovei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kupriyanova, E. K." box="[520,739,457,480]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="21 - 28" refId="ref62782" refString="Kupriyanova, E. K. (1993 b) Deep-water Serpulidae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from the Kurile-Kamchatka trench: 2. Genera Bathyditrupa, Bathyvermilia and Protis. Zoologichesky Zhurnal, 72, 21 - 28." type="journal article" year="1993">Kupriyanova, 1993b</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,739,457,512]" box="[151,378,489,512]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Number of species: 1</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,553,1314]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Tube free, curved but not coiled, white, opaque, rectangular in cross-section; collar-like rings absent. Granular overlay absent. Operculum inverse conical, with brown chitinous endplate, flat or slightly concave. Opercular ampulla gradually merges (constriction absent) into thick, rather triangular peduncle with pinnules, but without wings. Peduncle inserted as the second dorsal radiole on one side. Pseudoperculum absent. Arrangement of radioles semi-circular, up to 6 per lobe. Branchial eyes not observed. Inter-radiolar membrane and stylodes absent. Mouth palps not observed. 5 thoracic chaetigerous segments. Collar non-lobed, short, with entire edge. Tonguelets absent. Thoracic membranes short, ending at second thoracic segment. Collar chaetae limbate (
<figureCitation box="[349,443,824,850]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1844" box="[463,580,824,849]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[463,580,824,849]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Apomatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
chaetae absent (
<figureCitation box="[772,865,824,850]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Thoracic uncini saw-to-rasp-shaped, with up to 4 (?6) teeth in a row above peg, with about 15 curved teeth in a row in profile (
<figureCitation box="[1063,1157,862,888]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
). Anterior peg bifurcate in high-power microscopy, but clearly gouged when studied by SEM (
<figureCitation box="[968,1059,901,927]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9E</figureCitation>
). Thoracic triangular depression absent. Abdominal chaetae all capillary (
<figureCitation box="[654,752,940,966]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
), posterior ones slightly longer; abdominal uncini raspshaped (
<figureCitation box="[248,338,978,1004]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[166,1421,362,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-111@29.[153,1438,349,1850]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 9. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyditrupa hovei, ZMA V.Pol.5325. A—collar chaetae, B—fourth bundle of thoracic chaetae, C—anterior abdominal chaeta, D—third row of thoracic uncini, E—gouged pegs of posterior thoracic uncini from below, F—first row of abdominal uncini." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 9F</figureCitation>
). Achaetous anterior abdominal zone short, just one or two segments. Posterior glandular pad absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,553,1314]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,312,1055,1081]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remarks</emphasis>
. This abyssal species had only been reported from the Kurile-Kamchatka trench (
<bibRefCitation author="Kupriyanova, E. K." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="21 - 28" refId="ref62782" refString="Kupriyanova, E. K. (1993 b) Deep-water Serpulidae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from the Kurile-Kamchatka trench: 2. Genera Bathyditrupa, Bathyvermilia and Protis. Zoologichesky Zhurnal, 72, 21 - 28." type="journal article" year="1993">Kupriyanova 1993b</bibRefCitation>
). We studied 2 additional specimens from the North Pacific Ocean, collected by the R/V 
<emphasis box="[1304,1382,1095,1120]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Vityaz,</emphasis>
Sta. 3151, near the Emperor Seamounts, 
<geoCoordinate box="[582,712,1133,1159]" degrees="44" direction="north" minutes="28" orientation="latitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="15" seconds="3" value="44.4675">44°28'3'' N</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[721,856,1133,1159]" degrees="170" direction="east" minutes="07" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="15" seconds="0" value="170.11667">170°07'0''E</geoCoordinate>
, grab, 
<quantity box="[937,1029,1133,1159]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.237" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="m" value="5237.0">5237 m</quantity>
, ZMA V.Pol. 5326; Sta. 4370, NE off 
<collectingRegion box="[191,279,1172,1198]" country="United States of America" name="Hawaii" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Hawaii</collectingRegion>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[291,422,1172,1198]" degrees="26" direction="north" minutes="04" orientation="latitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="15" seconds="2" value="26.067223">26°04'2'' N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[434,585,1172,1198]" degrees="153" direction="west" minutes="49" orientation="longitude" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" precision="15" seconds="3" value="-153.8175">153°49'3'' W</geoCoordinate>
, grab, 
<quantity box="[663,753,1172,1198]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.05" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="m" value="6050.0">6050 m</quantity>
, ZMA V.Pol. 5325. The characteristic feature of the genus is a free, unattached tube similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berkeley" authorityYear="1835" box="[684,777,1211,1236]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Ditrupa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[684,777,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Ditrupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but rectangular in cross-section and without an outer hyaline layer (see 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[379,495,1248,1274]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">The tube</emphasis>
, p. 7). It is probably synonymous with 
<taxonomicName authority="Jager (2004: 140)" authorityName="Jager" authorityPageNumber="140" authorityYear="2004" box="[995,1381,1249,1275]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Nogrobs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="fide">
<emphasis box="[995,1151,1249,1274]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Nogrobs fide</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Jager, M." box="[1163,1381,1249,1275]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="121 - 249" refId="ref62313" refString="Jager, M. (2004) Serpulidae und Spirorbidae (Polychaeta sedentaria) aus Campan und Maastricht von Norddeutschland, den Niederlanden, Belgien und angrenzenden Gebieten. Geologisches Jahrbuch, A 157, 121 - 249." type="journal article" year="2004">Jäger (2004: 140)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, see remarks below (p. 69).
</paragraph>
